  "number": "1.13",
  "title": "Spot Rates and Forward Rates",
  "body": " Spot Rates and Forward Rates  In , we will meet spot rates and forward rates. A spot rate is an effective annual interest rate offered today (time 0) for investment for a period of time. For example, the spot rate is the annual rate offered now for a 1-year investment, and is the annual rate offered now for a 2-year investment. A forward rate is a 1-year rate over a period that is implied by spot rates. So given and , there is an implied forward rate  for the time between Years 1 and 2. There zeros in the subscripts just indicate that we are thinking of investments made today. Let us take a look at how this works!    Suppose we have spot rates for a 1-year investment today and for a 2-year investment today.    Generate an interest rate timeline. Remember that is in effect between years 0 and 1, is a 1-year rate but in effect between years 0 and 2, and is a rate that is expected to be in effect between years 1 and 2.    In order for the market to work (based on the no-arbitrage rule ), the two options above must yield the same value at the end of the 2-year period. Use this to set up and solve an equation for .      Try another example. Suppose we have the following spot rates over three years:             1  1.5%    2  2.25%    3  2.5%     Find the implied forward rates , , and . Use a timeline to help!      Given spot rates , derive a formula for the forward rate . Use a timeline to help!      Given forward rates , derive a formula for the spot rate . Use a timeline to help!    "
