  "body": " Actuarial Notation 1 --  Actuaries have their own notation that they use for finance. Their notation can often declutter formulas, but at a price of making them more difficult to understand.  We have already met some actuarial notation. The symbol is actuarial notation for a nominal interest rate. Our next bit of actuarial notation concerns present values.  In this course, you will find that present value formulas are often more elegant than their future value equivalents. Recall that the present value is related to the future value at time (written a little differently) is The expression is called the present value factor , and by itself is clunky to work with. Actuaries use for the present value factor. In this activity, we will explore the advantage and disadvantage of this notation.    An annuity (more precisely, annuity-immediate) is a sequence of payments made at the end of each period over a length of time. We want the payments to be equally spaced, meaning the time between each payment is the same. We will denote the payment amount by (which for now we assume to be constant), and the number of payments to be . This means we have payments of at the end of times .    Generate a timeline to represent such an annuity.    Let us consider the present value at time 0.    Find the present value of the th payment. Use the present value factor written as .    Write the present value of the annuity at time 0 as a sum of the present values of each payment, using the present value factor written as .      Recall from calculus that a geometric series is a series of the form While we will review geometric series later in this book, for now we will use the following formula to sum from 1 to :     Use our geometric series formula to find a closed-form formula for the present value of an annuity. Simplify the denominator as much as possible.      Actuaries us for the present value factor: If there is more than one interest rate (like and ), we put subscripts on : and .    Rewrite the original present value formula (relating and ) using .    Prove the identity ( Hint : Directly substitute the expression for on the left and simplify.)      Return to the present value of the annuity.    Rewrite your sum for the present value of an annuity from using .    Use our geometric series formula, together with the identity from , to sum your series from Simplify the denominator as much as possible (and write the denominator in terms of ).      Annuities show up throughout this course. Here are a couple of examples.     is about loans. If someone is paying back a loan, the outstanding balance after the th payment is the present value (at time ) of the remaining payments. This is called the prospective form of the outstanding balance formula (it looks forward, prospectively, to the upcoming payments). Using for the payments, and using interest rate , find a formula for the outstanding balance after payments.    A bond involves    an equally-spaced sequence of payments of , called coupon payments, followed by    a final lump sum paid with the last coupon payment called the redemption amount .    The coupon payments use a rate called the coupon rate applied to something called the face value . So the coupon payments are (often ). The interest rate is used for valuation, and often .  The price of the bond is the present value of the coupon payments and the redemption amount. Find a formula for the price of a bond with coupon payments of , redemption amount , and interest rate .      State one advantage and one disadvantage of using for the present value factor.    "
