  "number": "6.1",
  "title": "General Principles of Loan Amortization",
  "body": " General Principles of Loan Amortization  When a loan is paid off, each payment has two components: the amount of interest paid , and the amount of principal paid, :   This notation sometimes vary from one text to another, so just be sure to understand the symbols you are using in any given context.  When loans are paid off, we say the loan is amortized. The word amortization refers to the payment of an original loan amount carrying a periodic interest rate with periodic payments . Sometimes there are different interest rates over different periods. Note that sometimes repayment schedules with constant payments ( for all ) is referred to as amortization or \"the amortization method.\" We try to avoid such terms in this book, but generally you can determine what the author means by context.  There are two general principles for loan amortization. The first is that the outstanding balance at any point in time is the present value of the remaining payments . In other words: Note that and as a consequence:   The second principle is what I call the recursive nature of amortization. If we start with , interest is accrued on this outstanding balance before the payment is applied.    Let's express the second principle with a couple of formulas.    Express using only and .    Express using only , , and .    Explain why I refer to this as recursive.      The following problem is from Broverman:  An amortized loan has 10 annual payments at the end of each year starting one year from now. The first 5 payments are 1000 each and the final 5 payments are 500 each. Interest is at an effective annual rate of 10%. Find each of the following:    The initial amount on the loan.    The outstanding balance just after the third payment.    The interest and principal in the fourth payment.    The outstanding balance just after the 8th payment.      An amortization schedule is a list that tracks payments, interest payments, principal payments, and the outstanding balance for each payment of the loan.  A loan of 100,000 carries an effective annual interest rate of . It is repaid with ten annual payments of 12,329.09 at the end of each year.  Complete the following amortization schedule for the first three years of the loan.        Payment  Interest Due  Principal Repaid  Outstanding Balance    0  -  -  -       1                2                3                    ðŸ§® Calculator Corner  The financial calculator includes an amortization worksheet This worksheet will tell you how much principal and how much interest is in a given payment, as well as the balance immediately following the payment. It can only be used when your are amortizing with constant payments ( for all ).  To use the amortization worksheet, first enter all of the data that you have about the loan using N , I\/Y , PV , PMT , and FV . Have the calculator calculate any missing values.  Once that is entered, hit the AMORT button (hit 2ND followed by the PV button). For P1, enter the payment number you want to look at, and hit ENTER . Then hit the button, and for P2, enter the same payment number and hit ENTER (if P1 and P2 are different, the calculator will report the cumulative impact, as we will see later!).  Then you can use the and buttons and see the outstanding balance immediately after the payment (BAL), the principal repaid in the payment (PRN), and the interest in the payment (INT). The principal and interest payments will display as negative due to the sign convention of the calculator.     Use the financial calculator to redo the previous question. Do you prefer to use the amortization worksheet or amortizing by hand?    Almost every problem we will examine will involve a loan being repaid by one of three approaches:    Constant payments: for all (the most common approach),    Constant payments of principal: for all , or    Payment of interest only ( for all ), with principal paid off at the end.      A loan of 50,000 has a term of 5 years. The effective annual interest rate is . Construct the amortization schedule under each of the following repayment conditions:    The loan is repaid with five annual level payments.    The loan is repaid with five payments. Each payment consists of the outstanding interest plus a 10,000 payment of principal.    The annual payments consist only of interest, and the balance is paid off at the end of the term.      What did you notice about the amortization schedules in the previous question?      Sometimes an interest rate changes during the term of a loan. Suppose a loan of 100,000 is paid off with ten annual payments. For the first four years, the interest rate is 6%, and for the last six years, the interest rate is 7.5%. The first four payments are 13,586.80. The last six payments are .    Find .    Find     Find       Suppose the interest rate does not change during the life of a loan. Then we have the following identity (which is very useful, especially in \"puzzle problems\"):     Verify this identity.    Rewrite the identity under the assumption that we have constant payments.    Still assuming constant payments, use this identity to write an equation for using only and .    Let's look at an example of a \"puzzle problem\" that this identity helps us solve.  Suppose we have a loan carries an effective monthly interest rate of and is paid off with monthly payments of 800. If , find .      You might run into a problem that does not quite fit into one of the three repayment approaches we outlined above. In these cases, it is helpful to write out two or three rows of an amortization schedule and look for patterns. To find patterns, it is helpful to write out your calculation steps.    A 30-year loan of 1000 is repaid with payments at the end of each year. Each of the first ten payments equals the amount of interest due. Each of the next ten payments equals 150% of the amount of interest due. Each of the last ten payments is . The lender charges interest at an effective annual rate of 10%. Calculate .    We can characterize the repayment in the middle ten payments in this problem as payment by multiples of interest. We could derive formulas for such a repayment scheme. Is it worth it? Why or why not?      This activity covered a lot of ground, all of which forms the foundation for the rest of the chapter. Write down three important points that come out of this activity.    "
