  "number": "6.4",
  "title": "Final Payments",
  "body": " Final Payments  When a loan is paid off with level payments, there is often a need to alter the final payment. This introduces balloon payments and drop payments .    Let's look at an example.    A loan of 5000 is being repaid with periodic payments of 300. The periodic effective interest rate is 2%. How many payments must be made to pay off the loan?    What is the issue with your answer?    To deal with the issue you identified, we make modifications to the final payment so that the loan is paid off.    One modification is a balloon payment . This is what we do when we round the number of payments down and make the final payment larger than the other payments.    What do you need to calculate in order to find the amount that must be added to the last regular payment?    Find the amount of a balloon payment in our example.    The other option is a drop payment . We add an extra payment to the payment schedule, and this payment is a smaller than the other payments.  What do you need to do in order to find the drop payment?    Calculate the amount of a drop payment in our example.     ðŸ§® Calculator Tip  You can find the amount of a balloon or drop payment in your calculator:    First, enter in all of your loan information and have the calculator CPT  N .    Next, round your value of down, enter the result for N , and CPT  FV .    For a balloon payment, add the result to the regular payment. For a drop payment, hit Â± , enter as PV , enter 1 for N , 0 for PMT , and CPT  FV .       (Problem 15) Prince Akeem of Zamunda borrows 75,000 to purchase a car. The loan carries an interest rate of 2.5% convertible monthly. The loan will be paid off with payments of 1643 at the end of each month for 4 years, with a balloon payment at the end.    Find the amount of the original balloon payment.    Suppose he decides to round up his monthly payment to 2000 (starting with the first payment), and complete his payoff with a drop payment instead of a balloon payment. Find the number of payments of 2000 he will make, and find the amount of the drop payment.      Sometimes a problem will tell you how many payments there are, and that the last payment is larger or smaller than the other payments. In this case, you are given and the th payment is either a balloon payment or a drop payment. This means that there are exactly regular payments. If you are not told the regular payments, you can calculate them as usual, but then round to adjust for the balloon payment or drop payment.    If you round the regular payment down, will the final payment be a little larger or a little smaller than the regular payment? Why?    If you round the regular payment up, will the final payment be a little larger or a little smaller than the regular payment? Why?      C.J. Cregg is paying off a loan of 45,000 loan with monthly payments for 3 years. There will be level payments followed by a slightly reduced final payment. The effective monthly interest rate is 3.5%. Find the amount of the final payment.      Part of finding a final payment is finding the outstanding balance immediately following the last regular payment. Do you use the prospective or retrospective method to do this? Why?    "
