  "title": "",
  "body": "  We have a few final definitions, as well as some assumptions, to introduce.    The time to the final payment is called maturity , and when the final payment occurs, the bond is said to have matured . This is often measured in years.    When , we often say that the bond is a par-valued bond, or a bond that is redeemed at par .    When the frequency of coupon payments is unstated, they are assumed to be semiannual .    Unless otherwise stated, coupon rates and yield rates are quoted as nominal rates, convertible at the same frequency as the coupon payments.      A par-valued bond has a face value of 1000, a coupon rate of 10%, and matures in 10 years. The yield rate is 12%. Determine the coupon payments, , and the present value.    A bond with a face value of 2000 has annual coupons at a rate of 8%, matures in 15 years, and is redeemed at par. The yield rate is 6%. Determine the coupon payments, , and the present value.    A bond with a face value of 1000, a coupon rate of 9%, and matures in 12 years with a redemption amount of 1250. The yield rate is 10%. Determine the coupon payments, , and the present value.   "
