  "title": "U.S. T-Bills vs Canadian T-Bills",
  "body": " U.S. T-Bills vs Canadian T-Bills  We will now look at differences between T-Bills in the United States and Canada. Recall that T-Bills are zero-coupon bonds that mature in less than one year. There are two differences between T-Bills in the U.S. and Canada. For U.S. T-Bills, we quote the yield rate as simple discount and use a 360-day year. For Canadian T-Bills, we quote the yield rate as simple interest and use a 365-day year.  Let's fix our notation before we start. Given a T-Bill, whether in the U.S. or Canada, we let be the number of days until maturity, the price (i.e. ), be the maturity value, and be the amount of interest (or discount). In addition, will be the rate of simple discount (in the U.S.) or simple interest (in Canada).    Find a relationship between , , and . This relationship is true in both the U.S. and Canada.      Next we find a formula for the quoted rate on a U.S. T-Bill. In the U.S., the quoted rate is a simple discount rate, and we use a 360-day year.    Write down an equation for .    Solve your equation for the quoted rate and express using , , and .    Find the quoted rate on a T-bill issued in the U.S with 37 days to maturity, a maturity value of 100, with interest of 0.15.      Now we will turn to a formula for the quoted rate on a Canadian T-Bill. In Canada, the quoted rate is a simple interest rate, and we use a 365-day year.    Write down an equation for .    Solve your equation for the quoted rate and express using , , and .    Find the quoted rate on a T-bill issued in Canada with 91 days to maturity, interest of 1.25, priced at 87.50.      A 90 day U.S. T-Bill can be purchased at with a quoted rate of 2.8%.  A 180-day Canadian T-Bill can be purchased at .  Both T-Bills mature at 10,000.  Calculate the quoted rate for the Canadian T-Bill.      Summarize the difference between U.S. and Canadian T-Bills in a table.    "
